@newcodebook 
Just to clarify the test setup (in the logs): Only the very first message/test used the proxy API. All subsequent tests were run using OpenClaw's native OAuth provider (google-gemini-cli)—but both were using the exact same underlying account. The difference is night and day. You can clearly see that when using the API endpoint, the model responds blazingly fast and actually feels "smarter" (e.g., it knows how to chunk/stream its responses naturally). However, the moment I switch to the native OAuth adapter, it not only becomes painfully slow, but it also only outputs monolithic blocks of text all at once. Honestly, even the reasoning quality/IQ feels noticeably degraded when forced through the OAuth path.
[openclaw-2026-03-06.log](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/25776044/openclaw-2026-03-06.log)

@newcodebook 
Pro tip for reviewing these:

I’ve found that placing these logs into the designated OpenClaw log directory allows them to be viewed directly within the OpenClaw Web UI. It provides a much cleaner, chronological visualization of the tool-calling timeline compared to raw terminal output. I highly recommend checking them out there for a more intuitive look at the exact "hang" intervals!

## Proposed Fix

I've identified the issue and have a patch ready. The fix involves setting explicit file permissions when writing cron files:

### Changes needed:

**src/cron/store.ts** (line 86):
```diff
- await fs.promises.writeFile(tmp, json, "utf-8");
+ await fs.promises.writeFile(tmp, json, { encoding: "utf-8", mode: 0o600 });
```

**src/cron/run-log.ts** (line 128):
```diff
- await fs.writeFile(tmp, `${kept.join("\n")}\n", "utf-8");
+ await fs.writeFile(tmp, `${kept.join("\n")}\n", { encoding: "utf-8", mode: 0o600 });
```

**src/cron/run-log.ts** (lines 142-143):
```diff
- await fs.mkdir(path.dirname(resolved), { recursive: true });
- await fs.appendFile(resolved, `${JSON.stringify(entry)}\n", "utf-8");
+ await fs.mkdir(path.dirname(resolved), { recursive: true, mode: 0o700 });
+ await fs.appendFile(resolved, `${JSON.stringify(entry)}\n", { encoding: "utf-8", mode: 0o600 });
```

This follows the pattern used in `src/infra/device-auth-store.ts` which uses `mode: 0o600` for sensitive files.

I can submit this as a PR once I resolve a fork issue on my end.

